metadata.name: Earth #220
metadata.description:
This artwork builds upon the annual Earth Day animations I’ve been making since 2009. The particle system was written from scratch in vanilla javascript (a single 22KB HTML/JS file). The particles are constrained to the surface of a sphere and exhibit "social interactions" from which life-like patterns emerge.

Each animation will be minted with a randomly assigned color palette, energy level, particle type, and social behavior. Over 900 basic phenotypes are possible, with countless subtleties expressed per phenotype. There are a few wild rarities waiting to be born as well...

This work evolved over a three day creative sprint with fellow algorithmic artist Canton Becker. We think the Earth deserves a blockchain that doesn't blow tons of carbon. This animation pays tribute to the climate scientists and tech innovators who are working to secure our future on this planet. To that end, 10% of all proceeds from this project will be donated to The Coalition for Rainforest Nations.

metadata.name: chorégraphie #303
metadata.description:
… divided in two,
like the parent in sound and motion.
yet not exactly the same, I get …


chorégraphie explores the algorithmic characteristics of recursion in audiovisual form.

The algorithm performs a recursive split. At each split stage, space is divided into four different sized quadrants. Each split stage will eventually spawn an oscillator or a synthesizer representing the current properties of recursion in sound. The process is recursively repeated until a maximum recursion depth is reached or an early return condition is met.
Additionally, an initial motion funnction is randomly selected and propageted through the recursion, so that each recursive split stage with move depending on it’s split properties in combination with time.

Click into the piece to start the audio. Each piece can be seeded with a new initial configuration by pressing the ‘s’ key.

© 2022 — Guido Schmidt

Created with:
p5, tone, @thi.ng/color, random

metadata.name: RAUSCH #145
metadata.description:
RAUSCH is a series of generative artworks that explore imaginary digital architectures. 

This series challenges traditional notions of architectural representation and raises important questions about the role of resolution in design. Just as the pixel resolution of an image affects its perceived quality, the resolution of an architectural space can affect its qualities and livability. By embracing digital variation through codes, this series explores the interplay between abstract and concrete space through multiple resolutions. 

RAUSCH is inspired by the feeling of being overwhelmed by complex, chaotic and messy sensations, and aims to engage the viewer through a sense of wonder, disorientation, and awe.

Released on the occasion of Companions of Code, a group exhibition by VerticalCrypto Art at The NFT Gallery in London. 
Curated by Micol Ap. Exhibition 10-24 February 2023

metadata.name: Element #29
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Shattered Obelisks #25
metadata.description:
Shattered Obelisks began as a work that is dedicated to my habit of mindlessly drawing on paper when I am stressed, depressed or immersed in difficult thoughts.

Like a patient undergoing psychotherapy and piecing together the causes of unconscious fears and anxieties, I and my artwork have assembled ourselves into something shaped, found order in the chaos and separated it from the external noise.

It took 3 months of continuous, obsessive work. I have developed a huge library, designed for hand-like drawing. The functionality of this library is four times larger than what is shown in this drop.

I plan to put this library out into the public domain when I deem it complete, and hope that it will help someone express themselves through the creative process as much as it helped for me.

In case you've encountered a problem with inverted colours, try changing browser or disabling extensions. This problem only occurred once during testing on a massive amount of devices and was resolved by disabling extensions.

IMPORTANT NOTES BLOCK:

NOTE 1: This artwork should be viewed at a browser scale of 100%. Reducing the scale will increase the amount of detail, but may unpredictably affect the preservation of the location of secondary objects.

NOTE 2: This work can be printed on a plotter. Click S for saving it in .SVG.
Detailed instructions and answers to possible questions can be found in the console output of the code.

NOTE 3: This drop is the first one from the series of 3. It will be used as AL ticket in next drops of this series.

metadata.name: Brutal Infection #4
metadata.description:
Brutal Infection explores the concept of structural organisms from a dystopian vision.The use of muted colors reflects the cold and inhuman nature of the organisms, while also emphasizing the sense of evolution, emergence, and life within these structures.

The compositions are based on trigonometric functions, aligning geometric shapes into abstract forms, creating a sense of harmony and balance amidst the chaos and turmoil of the structural organisms.

The viewer is invited to examine the tiniest details, as they are the most interesting, alive, and emerging parts of the structures themselves.
___________________

Due to differences in how shaders operate in different engines, there may be slight differences between the preview image and the live-rendered output.

To obtain the live-rendered version, you can press the 's' key in live view or alternatively, you can right-click and save the preview image.

Made with p5js and glsl shaders.

Best experienced in fullscreen.
